At the risk of rehashing some debates of Fury vs. Mastery vs. Clarity, here's my take.<br>
<br>
At MC3, I'll get 3 mana per tick (6 seconds) free. That's an incremental 30 mana per minute. Shock of Firey Blades has a base cost of 334 mana. Let's say, hypothetically, I'm wearing an earing and that brings the cost down to about 300 mana. That means, that due to MC3, I'll get one extra cast of SoFB every 10 minutes in an exp grind group. That's not exactly what's going to cause me to med noticably less by itself.<br>
<br>
Where I see value in MC3 is once someone has made the &quot;leap&quot; to extreme mana regen gear/skills, which I have not yet done. If I had maxxed FT15 in items, Water form 3 and MC3, then we're talking, in aggregate, the mana regeneration is VERY substantial. When I have the AA points to spare, and have made the commitment to that route with other items and skills, then I will revisit this skill (as then, within the scope of that strategy, it has incremental value).<br>
<br>
I opted for Fury for one reason (well two):  Velk boots. Fury does meaningfully increase damage output over time, especially in conjuction with focus items. It also gives me a warm fuzzy feeling when guildies and groupmates see some nice damage output from me on occasion (besides the crit 8 damage nukes form when I'm pulling with burst of flame). A secondary, but lesser reason is PVP. Because it's so unpredictable, it's not super useful, but I've had several PVP crits for in excess of 1,300 damage and that's only with Fury2 (and remember, this is 66% of full damage nerfed). 1,300 damage will scare the crap out of a rogue, monk and kill most other unbuffed casters outright. I have a mage in my guild who has Fury3, and I've seen him PVP crit for 1500+. Now, it's not mana burn, but it's as good as we get. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->     <br>
<br>
Now, I opted for Casting Mastery over Mental Clarity because it is exceedingly rare when I cast something other than a conjuration spell (which is where my spec lies). Now, of course mana saved when making a specialization roll isn't quite so measurable, laregely because it varies, but in the course of 10 minutes of casting (especially in a mana dump situation on a big mob at raids), would I be willing to bet I saved more than the 300 mana with just CM2? Absolutely.<br>
<br>
Let's take this one last step further...<br>
<br>
Assuming I've maxxed out casting mastery, and I'm making a fair number of specialization rolls on my casts (let's say conservatively 40% of casts on SoFB) and let's say that when I've made my specialization rolls, I saved conservatively 25% of the mana costs on average. Let's also assume I'm wearing a bauble for mana conservation's sake.<br>
<br>
This means over 10 casts of SoFB with a base cost of 300 (due to earing), I spent (6*300) + (4*225) =  2,700 mana. This is an average cost of 270 mana per cast.<br>
<br>
Assuming then, I go and max out Mental Clarity3, that means I get an extra cast of SoFB every 9 minutes as opposed to every 10 minutes... that's an 11% increase in efficiency because of the reduced average costs of casting that spell as opposed to not having Casting Mastery.<br>
<br>
Having mastery first, makes investing in clarity later, more worthwhile (but still not enoughm IMO to make it a higher priority than some other skills). Mind you, this also doesn't take into account the mana savings in the reduction of fizzle rate. Your milage may vary depending upon how much you raid, PVP, or exp grind.<br>
<br>
I probably put also /pet hold higher on the list than most, because again, I see one of it's key uses as PVP. No longer will people train my pet to mobs, in hopes that the mobs will pull my pet off them (the mobs will still eventually kill pet and come for me but not until after my pet kills my quarry, which is my main goal). The PVE benefits of /pet hold, are also nice of course... but they are secondary to me for the most part.<br>
<br>
Someone correct me if I'm wrong, but this was the logic I used to make the determination of where to put my points...<br>
